[[Image:Gulf of the Farallones NMS map.jpg|thumb|300px|Map of the Gulf of the Farallones National Marine Sanctuary, showing the location of the Gulf itself within]] '''Gulf of the Farallones''' is a [[:wikt:gulf|gulf]] of the [[Pacific Ocean]] off the northern [[California]] coast.<ref>[http://www.topozone.com/map.asp?lat=37.82893&lon=-122.53841&datum=nad83&u=4&layer=DRG&size=l&s=1000 USGS], 09-18-07</ref> It extends westward from the opening of the [[San Francisco Bay]] and [[Drakes Bay]] to the [[Farallon Islands]]. Most of the gulf lies in [[Gulf of the Farallones National Marine Sanctuary]], which protects about {{convert|1250|sqmi|km2}}.
The gulf is home to major shipping lines to the [[Port of San Francisco]], [[Port of Oakland]], and [[Port of Richmond (California)|Port of Richmond]]. The gulf has also historically been used as a dumping ground for various types of waste, including dredging sediment, industrial waste, sunk vessels, and barrels of low-level nuclear waste.<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/22018113 ''Beyond the Golden Gate'', pages 60-71]</ref> Around 47,800 barrels of nuclear waste were dumped between 1946 and 1970; their location was largely unknown until mapping and monitoring efforts in the 1990s.<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/22018119 ''Beyond the Golden Gate'', pages 66]</ref>
''Farallones'' comes from the Spanish ''farallón'' meaning sea cliff and is a reference to the islands. Historical names for the gulf include Bahia De Puerto De San Francisco, Ensenada De Los Farallones, and La Bahia De Los Pinos.<ref name=gnis>{{gnis|1654437|Gulf of the Farallones}}</ref>
{{Coord|37.7504857|N|122.7516535|W|type:waterbody_scale:10000000|display=title|notes=<ref name=gnis/>}}
